Estimation of the Bulk Rock Density using Gravity Measurements

Underground Practical Course at TUBAF Himmelfahrt Fundgrube

Author

Dr. Ralph-Uwe Börner
TU Bergakademie Freiberg
Institute of Geophysics and Geoinformatics

Published

February 16, 2026

1 Task

Using a Scintrex CG-5 quartz gravity meter, the density of the Freiberg grey gneiss is to be determined by vertical difference measurements in the Himmelfahrt Fundgrube shaft. The results of the investigations are to be interpreted.

2 Theoretical background

We consider the model of an infinite horizontal plate bounded by \(z=0\) and \(z=h\). The gravitational effect of this plate adds to the normal attraction \(\gamma_{0}\) of the ellipsoidal Earth. These two effects contribute to the gravity measured at the vertical levels \(z_{1}\) and \(z_{2}\):

\[ \begin{align} g(z_{1}) & = 2 \pi f \rho (h - 2 z_{1}) + \gamma_{0}(z_{1}) \\ g(z_{2}) & = 2 \pi f \rho (h - 2 z_{2}) + \gamma_{0}(z_{2}) \end{align} \] Subtracting the second equation from the first, we obtain the block density \(\rho\) with \[ \begin{align} \rho & = \frac{1}{4 \pi f} \left( \frac{\gamma_{0}(z_{2})-\gamma_{0}(z_{1})}{z_{2}-z_{1}}-\frac{g(z_{2}) - g(z_{1})}{z_{2}-z_{1}} \right) \\ & = \frac{1}{4 \pi f} \left( g_{z}-\frac{g(z_{2}) - g(z_{1})}{z_{2}-z_{1}} \right) \end{align} \]

with the free-air gravity gradient \(g_{z} = 0.3086\ \text{mGal/m}\).

In practice, the effect of cavities, shafts, tunnels, and terrain have to be considered. Their influence is not covered by this simplified model and has thus to be accounted for by gravity reductions.

3 Experimental setup

3.1 Gravity measurements

For reference, a vertical cross section of the shaft is shown below. The sketch illustrates the geometric configuration of the Himmelfahrt Fundgrube and the surrounding rock mass and indicates the position of the gravity meter during the experiment.

The gravity measurements are carried out using the double-loop method to ensure a reliable estimate of the instrument drift. The elevations of all measurement points are listed in Table 1.

The measurements begin at point P0, which serves as the base station. All gravity and height measurements are referenced to this point.

The drift-corrected relative gravitational acceleration is obtained from

\[ \Delta g(z) = g(z,t) - g_G(z_{0}, t), \]

where \(g_G(z_{0}, t)\) represents a linear interpolation through the base-point readings at fixed level \(z_{0}\), from which the instrument drift correction for the corresponding measurement times is derived.

For this experiment, no connection to national gravity networks is required. Therefore, \(\Delta g\) at point P0 is arbitrarily set to zero.

3.2 Location of the measurement points

3.3 Reduction of the measurements

In shaft gravimetry, free-air, Bouguer, and normal gravity reductions are omitted.

Only the following corrections are applied:

  • Gallery reduction \(\delta g_{\text{G}}\)
  • Shaft reduction \(\delta g_{\text{S}}\)
  • Cavity reduction \(\delta g_{\text{C}}\)
  • Terrain reduction \(\delta g_{\text{T}}\)

These reductions compensate for mining-related voids by computationally refilling them with mass.

For all reductions, a uniform density of

\[ \rho = 2.70 \times 10^3 \, \text{kg/m}^3 \]

is assumed, corresponding approximately to the density of the Freiberg ortho-gneiss.

3.3.1 Gallery reduction \(\delta g_{G}\)

The influence of the tunnels, adits, or galleries is approximated by a horizontal two-dimensional rectangular prism. Required parameters are the tunnel height \(H\), width \(B\), and the position \((x, h)\) of the measurement point with respect to the tunnel walls.

TipPython

We use the Python function gz_prism.py (see Section 6).

While a right-handed coordinate system with downward-pointing \(z\) is used in general, the gravity reduction is formulated here in a coordinate frame defined by the width and height of the tunnel cross section.

Consequently, the third argument in the call to gz_prism.py is H-h, where H denotes the tunnel height and h the elevation of the gravimeter above ground.

Note further that the infinite prism is approximated by placing the bounding planes \(y=\pm\mathrm{const}\) at sufficiently large distances from the plane \(y=0\).

g = gz_prism(obs=(x, 0.0, H-h), prism=(0, B, -1000.0, 1000.0, 0.0, H), rho=2700)

3.3.2 Shaft reduction \(\delta g_{S}\)

The shaft effect is approximated by a vertical rectangular prism. Required parameters are the shaft dimensions defined by the diagonal between the points \((x_{1}, y_{1}, z_{1})\) and \((x_{2}, y_{2}, z_{2})\), the coordinates of the gravity meter position \((x, y, z)\), and the reduction density.

A rectangular horizontal cross section is uniquely defined by the diagonally opposite corner points \((x_1, y_1)\) and \((x_2, y_2)\), while the vertical extent ranges from \(z_1\) to \(z_2\). Numerical values are summarized in Table 1.

TipPython

We use the Python function gz_prism.py.

Here, x, y, z denote the coordinates of the gravity meter position. The vertical coordinate must be taken as depth, according to the values listed in Table 1.

g = gz_prism(obs=(x, y, z), prism=(x1, x2, y1, y2, 0.0, 229.0), rho=2700)

3.3.3 Terrain reduction \(\delta g_{T}\)

Only the gravity effect of the stock piling is considered. The reduction is applied with respect to the stock base, located 10 m below the hanging bank. The terrain is approximated by a three-dimensional rectangular prism.

For measurements at P3, \(\delta g_T > 0\).
For all underground measurement points, \(\delta g_T < 0\).

TipPython

We use the Python function gz_prism.py.

An area-equivalent rectangle is used to approximate the polygonal cross section of the pile.

3.3.4 Cavity Reduction \(\delta g_{C}\)

Right below the measurement point P2, a cavity (Radstube) is present. As a consequence, at this point a cavity reduction is required, using a three-dimensional rectangular prism formulation.

TipPython


We use the Python function gz_prism.py.

The coordinates can be taken from Figure 2.

A coordinate system with downward-pointing \(z\) is adopted. The elevation of the instrument above the gallery floor must be considered. The cavity extends from \(y_1 = -1.3,\mathrm{m}\) to \(y_2 = +1.3,\mathrm{m}\), and the gravity meter is positioned at \(y=0\).

3.4 Measurements

A standard form is provided for the gravity measurements.

The instrument drift correction is performed by linear interpolation.

The reduced relative gravitational acceleration is computed as

\[ \Delta g_{\text{red}} = \Delta g + \delta g_{\text{G}} + \delta g_{\text{S}} + \delta g_{\text{C}} + \delta g_{\text{T}}. \]

If repeated measurements are available, the mean drift-corrected value \(\Delta g\) must be determined first, and all reductions are applied afterwards.

4 Estimation of the block density

The block density \(\rho_B\) represents the mean density of the rock layer between two or more gravimetric measurements obtained at different depth levels.

Let \(\Delta g_1(z_1)\) and \(\Delta g_2(z_2)\) be the reduced relative gravitational accelerations at the upper and lower measurement points. Then

\[ \rho_B = \frac{1}{4\pi f} \left( g_z - \frac{\Delta g_2 - \Delta g_1}{z_2 - z_1} \right) = \frac{1}{4\pi f}(g_z - g_h), \]

where the free-air gravity gradient is

\[ g_z = 0.3086 \ \text{mGal/m}. \]

4.2 Plots

The following quantities should be plotted:

  • \(\Delta g\), \(\Delta g_{\text{red}}\), and \(\Delta g_{\text{theo}}\) as functions of depth
  • \(\rho_B\) as a density–depth function

Here, \(\Delta g_{\text{theo}}\) denotes the theoretical vertical gradient of the relative gravitational acceleration for an assumed block density of

\[ \rho = 2.70 \times 10^3 \, \text{kg/m}^3. \]

5 Interpretation and discussion of limitations and uncertainties

The following aspects must be discussed and their influence on the derived block density evaluated:

  • Accuracy of shaft and tunnel surveying
  • Instrument drift
  • Terrain reduction
TipProblem set
  • Which reduction exerts the strongest influence on the final result?
  • How would you modify the reductions to obtain a more realistic estimate of the block density?
  • Which implicit assumptions underlie the adopted density of the gneiss block?

6 Appendix

import numpy as np

def gz_prism(obs=(0.0, 0.0, 0.0), prism=(1.0, 2.0, 1.0, 2.0, 1.0, 2.0), rho=2700.0):
    """
    Calculate the vertical gravity component gz (after Nagy 1966)
    at point (x, y, z) for a homogeneous rectangular prism.

    Parameters
    ----------
    obs : tuple
        Observation point x, y, z (in m)
    prism : tuple
        Prism boundaries (x1, x2, y1, y2, z1, z2) in m
        (z1 and z2 relative to the same reference level as z)
    rho : float
        Density contrast (kg/m³)

    Returns
    -------
    gz : float
        Vertical gravity component (in mGal)
    """
    G = 6.67430e-11
    x, y, z = obs
    x1, x2, y1, y2, z1, z2 = prism
    gz = 0.0

    for i, xi in enumerate([x1 - x, x2 - x]):
        for j, yj in enumerate([y1 - y, y2 - y]):
            for k, zk in enumerate([z1 - z, z2 - z]):
                sgn = (-1)**(i + j + k)
                r = np.sqrt(xi**2 + yj**2 + zk**2)
                gz += sgn * (
                    xi * np.log(yj + r)
                    + yj * np.log(xi + r)
                    - zk * np.arctan((xi * yj) / (zk * r))
                )

    return G * rho * gz * 1e5
